Your wife was fully at fault *because* she pulled &quot;into oncoming traffic.&quot;
If your wife wishes to sue the state for the dangerous intersection, she
is presumably free to do so but that has no bearing on your wife's standing
in the accident. I've been through this with my son--his first car and he
had it less than
two weeks. He pulled out from a blind intersection and was hit by a speeding
motorist. My son's car was totally spun around by the impact (speed limit
was 25 mph
in town) who clipped the rear of my son's car. It was totaled. He almost
made it through the intersection,
said the officer, and no one was charged. The cop said if he charged anyone,
he would charge both.
He charged neither. The insurance co. didn't care. My son was totally at
fault for insurance purposes.
He is also a very very careful driver now ;-)
