"/> Let's see, you want to sue the STATE because they allow on street
parking???

Could your wife see the car coming or not? If she could she should have
stopped. If she couldn't see the other car she has no way of telling how
fast it was going.

A bumper can be completely torn off by a car going 5 MPH. Have doubts?
Then look for copies of the most recent 5 MPH accident test results on
SUVs. The damages were $500 to $3500 when backing into a post. A car
going 5 to 10 MPH would easily peel off the rear bumper.

If the other driver was indeed going 30, you are lucky the car only grazed
the bumper of your car. Had it hit the rear quarter panel or rear wheel
of your car broadside your car would likely have been totaled.

I notice you cite the use of the word obstruction in the police report,
but you don't cite the report of the other driver's speed.

You wife moved into the right of way of another car. Based on your
story, your wife is at fault.

(Note that you use the feminine pronoun so frequently it is impossible to
tell who you are talking about.)

